<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-369-226  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 369 226.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  May 1990 v8 n5 p15(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font wars, part II: the battle for your desktop. (Richard Landry)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Landry, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Today's leading word processing programs contain the desktoppublishing power to create professional business documents.andP;  Pagedescription languages, or software programs that translate complextype and graphics formats into printer commands, are declining inimportance.andP;  Today's font and graphics technologies are notattractive to MS-DOS users because Adobe PostScript printers areslower and more costly than other LaserJets and require hugeamounts of memory and costly license fees from Adobe.andO;Font-creation programs also require huge amounts of hard diskspace and are difficult to set up.andP;  Clone software and PostScriptcartridges are lower-cost alternatives, but speed andcompatibility issues can be problems.andP;  Font and printer controlsbuilt into the new generation of software will make it easier tocreate professional looking documents.andP;  IBM will provide AdobePostScript fonts in its operating systems.andP;  Microsoft is teamingwith Apple to develop a better version of PostScript.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   PostScript (Printer software) (usage).andO;Topic:     FontsPage Description LanguagesDesktop PublishingWord ProcessingSoftware Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>